The [Post-Attack Command and Control System](/Post-Attack_Command_and_Control_System) Facility in Hadley, Massachusetts, represents a rather stark monument to a particular era of human anxiety and ingenuity. Decommissioned now, this subterranean stronghold once stood as a critical component of the [Strategic Air Command](/Strategic_Air_Command)'s elaborate plans for surviving, and perhaps even orchestrating, a post-[nuclear war](/Nuclear_warfare) world. Located rather discreetly on and beneath [Bare Mountain](/Bare_Mountain_(Massachusetts)) in [Hadley, Massachusetts](/Hadley,_Massachusetts), at coordinates 42°18′15.13″N 72°32′6.37″W, it operated with a grim purpose from its inauguration on June 2, 1958, until its eventual closure in 1970.

This hardened underground facility was known by a variety of names, each hinting at its layered functions and the pervasive secrecy of its existence. It was officially the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) Combat Operations Center (COC), a designation that certainly didn't roll off the tongue with the same ominous weight as its unofficial moniker, "The Bunker." Locals also referred to it simply as "The Notch," a nod to the adjacent pass, or the "Westover Communications Annex," due to its integral operational relationship with the nearby [Westover Air Force Base](/Westover_Air_Reserve_Base). Regardless of what one called it, its primary role was unambiguous: to provide a secure, survivable command and control center in the event of a catastrophic global conflict.

Designed with an almost unsettling foresight, the facility boasts two subterranean stories, encompassing a considerable 40,000 square feet (approximately 3,700 square meters) of hardened space. Within these concrete and steel confines, it was engineered to comfortably house a contingent of 135 military personnel, presumably those deemed essential for the continuation of... well, whatever came next. Its operational lifespan notably included the terrifying days of the [Cuban Missile Crisis](/Cuban_Missile_Crisis), a period when its theoretical purpose edged alarmingly close to becoming a chilling reality. The very framework of its old command room computer area, complete with its now-iconic [raised floor](/Raised_floor), speaks volumes about the technological backbone intended to support the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) during humanity's potential final act.

## History

The genesis of the [Post-Attack Command and Control System](/Post-Attack_Command_and_Control_System) Facility in Hadley can be traced back to 1957, a year when the shadow of the [Cold War](/Cold_War) loomed particularly long and cold over the [United States](/United_States). It was then that the [Strategic Air Command](/Strategic_Air_Command), ever vigilant and perpetually planning for the worst-case scenario, initiated the construction of a robust, hardened bunker. This wasn't merely a storage depot or a minor outpost; it was intended to serve as the critical command post for the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force), an entity then strategically headquartered at the nearby [Westover Air Force Base](/Westover_Air_Reserve_Base) in [Chicopee, Massachusetts](/Chicopee,_Massachusetts).

The choice of location — specifically, deep within the natural defenses of [Bare Mountain](/Bare_Mountain_(Massachusetts)), just off [Route 116](/Massachusetts_Route_116) — was no accident. The mountain itself provided a significant degree of natural shielding, which was then augmented by extensive engineering to create a structure hardened against the devastating effects of a direct [nuclear blast](/Nuclear_explosion). This hardening was designed to mitigate not only the initial concussive force but also the subsequent, lingering threats of radiation and electromagnetic pulse (EMP), ensuring that senior military staff could maintain operational capabilities and, presumably, facilitate further military actions in a world irrevocably altered. The grim practicality of such a design is, frankly, breathtaking.

During its operational years, from 1958 to 1970, the facility was not an isolated island of command. It was intricately woven into the broader military communication network through a series of crucial microwave transmission links. These vital connections extended to other key communication hubs, including ATT Blackstone, [ATT Chesterfield](/ATT_Chesterfield), and ATT Peru. Such a robust and redundant communication infrastructure was absolutely paramount for ensuring the continuity of command and control, allowing the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) to remain responsive, even if the primary command structures above ground had been rendered inoperable. This intricate web of communication was the nervous system of a potentially decapitated military, a silent promise of ongoing, albeit grim, strategic oversight.

## Reuse

The era of its primary purpose, however, was finite. In 1970, a strategic realignment within the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) led to the relocation of the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) to Guam. With its original occupants departed, the [Post-Attack Command and Control System](/Post-Attack_Command_and_Control_System) Facility in Hadley found itself adrift, a relic of a past that, thankfully, never fully materialized. The military, having no further use for a redundant command center in Massachusetts, abandoned the site.

But a structure built to withstand Armageddon doesn't simply fade away. Instead, it entered a peculiar new chapter in its existence. The [Federal Reserve](/Federal_Reserve), with its own brand of contingency planning, recognized the bunker's inherent security. They swiftly took over the facility, repurposing it as a secure storage repository for their invaluable records. And, if the whispers and enduring legends are to be believed — and who wouldn't want to believe in such delightful irony? — they allegedly stored substantial sums of physical currency within its impenetrable walls. The intention, a rather bold and almost comically optimistic one, was for this cash reserve to be deployed to "restart the economy" in the aftermath of a widespread [nuclear war](/Nuclear_warfare). One can only imagine the utter futility of such an endeavor, yet the commitment to the idea speaks volumes about the human capacity for denial, or perhaps, desperate hope.

Today, the bunker's trajectory has veered sharply from military command and economic resurrection to the decidedly more serene world of academia. The facility now serves as a central library storage facility for the [Five Colleges](/Five_College_Consortium), a collaborative academic alliance in the Pioneer Valley. Volumes of human knowledge, rather than plans for human destruction, now quietly reside within its hardened shell. It’s a rather poetic, if utterly unintended, transformation.

Beyond its practical reuses, the facility has also briefly entered the realm of popular culture. Its stark, imposing architecture and inherent mystique made it a natural fit for cinematic drama. In 2010, the decommissioned bunker featured prominently in the [Mel Gibson](/Mel_Gibson) movie [Edge of Darkness](/Edge_of_Darkness_(2010_film)). The facility's unassuming front entrance stood in as the main access point for the fictional "Northmoor Facility" in the film, lending an air of authentic, clandestine operations to the narrative. Furthermore, the access road leading to the bunker, aptly named Military Road, was utilized during the initial stages of a pivotal pursuit scene, with Gibson's character commencing his chase of the facility director along its winding path. Hollywood, it seems, always finds a use for humanity's discarded anxieties.

## Units based there

Throughout its operational tenure as a vital component of the [Strategic Air Command](/Strategic_Air_Command)'s defense infrastructure, the [Post-Attack Command and Control System](/Post-Attack_Command_and_Control_System) Facility in Hadley hosted several critical military units, each contributing to its overarching mission of command continuity.

*   [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) (1958–1970)
*   814th Combat Defense Squadron (1958–1968)
*   99th Security Police Squadron (1968–1970)

